Self-educated, poor beyond imagining, John Clare experienced a brief, condescending vogue as England's "Peasant Poet," at a time when illiteracy was a norm for England's rural workers, and poets were expected to come from higher social ranks.

Into the nothingness of scorn and noise, Into the living sea of waking dreams,Where there is neither sense of life or joys, But the vast shipwreck of my life's esteems;Even the dearest, that I love the best,Are strange--nay, rather stranger than the rest.

Into the nothingness of scorn and noise, Into the living sea of waking dreams,Where there is neither sense of life or joys, But the vast shipwreck of my life's esteems;Even the dearest, that I love the best,Are strange--nay, rather stranger than the rest.
Lines such as "I am the self-consumer of my woes" have a distinction and force that need no propping up by the pathos of the life behind the writing.
